===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|frm|Madagascar}}, from ''Madageiscar'', popularly reputed as a corrupted transliteration of {{m|en|Mogadishu}} by {{w|Marco Polo}}'s misreading of Arabic. The maps of particular interest are that of [[w:al-Idrisi|al-Idrisi]] in the 12th century, who produced the [[w:Tabula Rogeriana|Tabula Rogeriana]], the most advanced world map at the time.

The actual misconstrued term was {{der|en|ar|جَزِيرَة المَالَائِيّ|tr=|t=The Island of Mālāī}} listed along side {{noncog|ar|جَزِيرَة القَمَر|tr=|t=The Island of the Moon}} which lent its named to [[w:Comoros|Comoros]]; Madagascar however likely being the original later based off of the dimensions.

The map in question warps the direction of Africa's east coast to be parallel alongside the coast of southeast Asia, prompting a conflation of the regions furthest east and furthest south, in the reaches of Arab exploration. This perhaps makes the Island of Mālāī both representing Madagascar and an island in Indonesia, likely [[w:Sumatra|Sumatra]] in close proximity to [[w:Malaysia|Malaysia]]. To conflate matters more so, the populations of both region are of [[w:Austronesian|Austronesian]] background, a thing pointed out by Arab explorers who identified Madagascar as colony of the former region. A second wave of Austronesians, including Malays, did indeed migrate to the island after the first group had originally left from what was likely Southern [[w:Borneo|Borneo]] from linguistic and genetic analysis.

"Mālāī-Gezīra" also holds connection to the term for the people and languages of the island, {{m|en|Malagasy}}, which had earlier forms {{m|en|Malegass}} and {{m|en|Madegass}}, because of dialect division.

